<subSubSection id="02C66578FFF9FFB8FF3D992968F37B06" pageId="20" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFF9FFB8FF3D992968F37B06" blockId="20.[151,757,1388,1639]" pageId="20" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFF9FFB8FF3D9929680578E4" bold="true" box="[151,264,1389,1413]" pageId="20" pageNumber="34">Remarks:</emphasis>
This species differs from the other species of 
<taxonomicName id="8DDC4D70FFF9FFB8FF1F99C9682B78C4" authorityName="LAMARCK" authorityYear="1812" box="[181,294,1421,1445]" class="Nodosariata" family="Nodosariidae" genus="Nodosaria" kingdom="Chromista" order="Nodosariida" pageId="20" pageNumber="34" phylum="Foraminifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFF9FFB8FF1F99C9682B78C4" box="[181,294,1421,1445]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="34">Nodosaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having no tumidity of chamber contour until late maturity. The test has longitudinal thick costae. 
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFF9FFB8FF3D998968C67884" bold="true" box="[151,459,1485,1509]" pageId="20" pageNumber="34">Stratigraphic distribution:</emphasis>
It is recorded in the Esna Shale by SAID &amp; KENAWY (1956) and in the Paleocene Midway fauna by BERGGREN &amp; AUBERT (1975). It is found in the Maastrichtian in addition to the Paleocene zones of the Esh El Mallaha area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
